div.p:
SSC, which is generally produced from single-crystalline Si wafers, tends to have higher efficiency because it has reduced charge recombination compared to MSC. These Si wafers are made by dicing cylindrical Si ingots grown by the Czochralski (Cz) method. A cylindrical Si ingot consists of a neck, shoulder, body and tail. The process of growing the body consumes the largest amount of time in the Cz production method, and therefore, reducing the time needed to grow the body is one of the critical strategies for enhancing productivity and reducing production costs [

 8

].

One of the disadvantages of SSC is light-induced degradation (LID) which occurs when boron is doped or an oxygen compound is formed because of the quartz crucibles [

 18

]. Even with n-type SSC, where phosphorus is used instead of boron, thus avoiding the LID [

 19

], oxygen compound formation is inevitable.

A feasible solution for this is to apply a magnetic field to the Si melt. The natural convection is suppressed by the magnetic viscosity, resulting in low oxygen concentration [

 20

]. As a further study, magnets will be installed on the current ingot growth chambers, and this is expected to suppress LID as well as improve cell efficiency.
